# Terminal Execution Rules

1. NEVER pipe python or test execution commands into `tail`, `head`, `less`, or log-limiting utilities (e.g., `2>&1 | tail -20`). This causes output buffering, blinds your context window, and leads to infinite execution loops.
2. ALWAYS execute python scripts and inline snippets natively so that standard output (stdout) and standard error (stderr) streams stream to the terminal in real time.
3. When writing one-off inline python strings (`python3 -c "..."`), always include `flush=True` in print statements to ensure the terminal outputs progress instantly.
4. If a script appears to take a long time (such as loading PyTorch or machine learning models), write brief, incremental status print statements so progress can be monitored.

# Background Processes & Long-Running Servers

1. When launching a background process or server using `&` or `nohup`, ALWAYS disconnect standard input by adding `< /dev/null` at the end of the background statement. (Example: `nohup python3 server.py > server.log 2>&1 < /dev/null &`). If you omit `< /dev/null`, the terminal session will hang indefinitely.
2. NEVER assume a background server is running successfully just because it echoed a Process ID (PID). 
3. ALWAYS verify your background tasks. Immediately after launching a background process, chain a sleep command followed by a log check or process check (e.g., `& sleep 2 && cat /tmp/server.log` or `curl localhost:port`). This ensures you catch immediate startup crashes (like port-in-use or missing dependencies) instead of looping.